**Insight**: As the range grows, lower-order bits inevitably take both 0 and 1 values, so they AND to 0. Only the **common high-order prefix** of `left` and `right` survives.

**Algorithm**: Right-shift both until they're equal; count shifts. The common prefix shifted back is the answer.

```javascript
function rangeBitwiseAnd(left, right) {
  let shift = 0;
  while (left !== right) {
    left >>>= 1;
    right >>>= 1;
    shift++;
  }
  return left << shift;
}
```

**Time**: O(log max). **Space**: O(1).

**Alternative — Brian Kernighan**: Repeatedly do `right = right & (right - 1)` while `right > left`; the answer is the final `right`. Both run in O(log max).

Use `>>>` (unsigned shift) in JS to avoid sign-bit pollution near the upper bound.

