editorial:
**Brute force**: O(n^2) — fine for n up to a few thousand.

**Greedy + hashing — O(32n)**: Build the answer bit-by-bit from the highest bit (30) down. At each step, hypothesize the answer has the next bit set and check whether two numbers in the array have prefixes (truncated to current bit depth) whose XOR equals the current candidate. Use a HashSet of prefixes for the lookup.

```javascript
function maxXorPair(nums) {
  if (nums.length < 2) return 0;
  let max = 0, mask = 0;
  for (let bit = 30; bit >= 0; bit--) {
    mask |= (1 << bit);
    const prefixes = new Set();
    for (const n of nums) prefixes.add(n & mask);
    const candidate = max | (1 << bit);
    for (const p of prefixes) {
      if (prefixes.has(candidate ^ p)) {
        max = candidate;
        break;
      }
    }
  }
  return max;
}
```

**Time**: O(31 * n). **Space**: O(n).

**Intuition**: For each bit position from highest to lowest, greedily try to make that bit 1 in the answer. If two prefixes p1, p2 satisfy `p1 ^ p2 == candidate`, then real numbers with those prefixes will produce an XOR ≥ candidate, so accept the bit. Otherwise drop it.

A bit-trie variant has the same asymptotics but is heavier to code.

